{"parse":{"title":"Smallpox demon","pageid":34004012,"revid":860087675,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Smallpox demon</b><span style=\"font-weight: normal\">&#32;(<span lang=\"ja\">Japanese: \u75b1\u7621\u795e</span><span style=\"display:none\">,</span>&#32;<i>H\u014ds\u014dshin</i>)</span> or <b>smallpox devil</b> is a demon which was believed to be responsible for causing <a href=\"/wiki/Smallpox\" title=\"Smallpox\">smallpox</a> in medieval Japan. In those days, people tried to appease the smallpox demon by assuaging his anger, or they tried to attack the demon since they had no other effective treatment for smallpox.\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:202px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Yoshitoshi_Driving_away_the_Demons.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/Yoshitoshi_Driving_away_the_Demons.jpg/200px-Yoshitoshi_Driving_away_the_Demons.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"305\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/Yoshitoshi_Driving_away_the_Demons.jpg/300px-Yoshitoshi_Driving_away_the_Demons.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/Yoshitoshi_Driving_away_the_Demons.jpg/400px-Yoshitoshi_Driving_away_the_Demons.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"464\" data-file-height=\"708\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Yoshitoshi_Driving_away_the_Demons.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><a href=\"/wiki/Minamoto_no_Tametomo\" title=\"Minamoto no Tametomo\">Minamoto no Tametomo</a> defeats a smallpox devil from <a href=\"/wiki/Yoshitoshi\" title=\"Yoshitoshi\">Yoshitoshi</a>'s 36 drawings of <a href=\"/wiki/Yokai\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Yokai\">Yokai</a></div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:202px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Shuran_Hososhin.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0/Shuran_Hososhin.jpg/200px-Shuran_Hososhin.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"259\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0/Shuran_Hososhin.jpg/300px-Shuran_Hososhin.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a0/Shuran_Hososhin.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"400\" data-file-height=\"517\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Shuran_Hososhin.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>A smallpox demon enshrined</div></div></div>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History_of_the_smallpox_demon_in_Japan\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History of the smallpox demon in Japan</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Customs_related_to_smallpox_devils\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Customs related to smallpox devils</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#The_red_treatment\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">The red treatment</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Finsen_and_the_red_light\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Finsen and the red light</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#Footnotes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Footnotes</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History_of_the_smallpox_demon_in_Japan\">History of the smallpox demon in Japan</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Smallpox_demon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History of the smallpox demon in Japan\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In Japanese, the word <i>h\u014ds\u014dshin </i>or <i>h\u014ds\u014dgami</i> (\u75b1\u7621\u795e (\u307b\u3046\u305d\u3046\u3057\u3093, \u307b\u3046\u305d\u3046\u304c\u307f\uff09) translates literally to \"<a href=\"/wiki/Smallpox\" title=\"Smallpox\">smallpox</a> god\". According to the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Shoku_Nihongi\" title=\"Shoku Nihongi\">Shoku Nihongi</a></i>, smallpox was introduced into Japan in 735 into Fukuoka Prefecture from Korea.  In those days, smallpox had been considered to be the result of <i><a href=\"/wiki/Onry%C5%8D\" title=\"Onry\u014d\">onry\u014d</a></i>, which was a mythological spirit from Japanese folklore who is able to return to the physical world in order to seek vengeance.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Smallpox-related <a href=\"/wiki/Kami\" title=\"Kami\">kamis</a>\ninclude <a href=\"/wiki/Sumiyoshi_sanjin\" title=\"Sumiyoshi sanjin\">Sumiyoshi sanjin</a> <sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> In a book published in the <a href=\"/wiki/Kansei\" title=\"Kansei\">Kansei</a> years (1789\u20131801), there were lines that wrote that smallpox devils were enshrined in families which had smallpox in order to recover from smallpox.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Customs_related_to_smallpox_devils\">Customs related to smallpox devils</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Smallpox_demon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Customs related to smallpox devils\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Smallpox devils were said to be afraid of red things and also of dogs; thus people displayed various dolls that were red. In <a href=\"/wiki/Okinawa\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Okinawa\">Okinawa</a>, they tried to praise and comfort devils with <a href=\"/wiki/Sanshin\" title=\"Sanshin\">sanshin</a>, an Okinawan musical instrument and lion dances before a patient clad in red clothes. They offered flowers and burned incense in order to please smallpox demon.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> \nIn Okinawa, there was smallpox poetry in <a href=\"/wiki/Ryuka_(poetry)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ryuka (poetry)\">Ryuka</a>; the purpose of smallpox poetry in the Ryukyu language is the glorification of the smallpox demon, or improvement from deadly infection of smallpox.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> There is a collection of smallpox poetry including 105 poems published in 1805.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> Traditional smallpox folk dances have been observed even in present-day Japan, including <a href=\"/wiki/Ibaraki_Prefecture\" title=\"Ibaraki Prefecture\">Ibaraki Prefecture</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Kagoshima_Prefecture\" title=\"Kagoshima Prefecture\">Kagoshima Prefecture</a>, for the avoidance of smallpox devils.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"The_red_treatment\">The red treatment</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Smallpox_demon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: The red treatment\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In European countries the \"red treatment\" was practiced from the 12th century onwards; when he caught smallpox, King <a href=\"/wiki/Charles_V_of_France\" title=\"Charles V of France\">Charles V of France</a> was dressed in a red shirt, red stockings, and a red veil.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/Elizabeth_I_of_England\" title=\"Elizabeth I of England\">Queen Elizabeth I</a> of England was likewise wrapped in a red blanket and placed by a live fire when she fell ill with smallpox in 1562, and similar treatments were applied to other European monarchs. In parts of India, China, Africa and Latin America, sacrifices were made to appease the gods of smallpox. In medieval Europe, prayer and pious living were recommended as one way to guard against sickness.  Many Japanese textbooks on <a href=\"/wiki/Dermatology\" title=\"Dermatology\">dermatology</a> stated that red light was able to weaken the symptoms of smallpox.<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> This was common in China, India, Turkey and <a href=\"/wiki/Georgia_(country)\" title=\"Georgia (country)\">Georgia</a>. In western Africa, the <a href=\"/wiki/Yoruba_religion\" title=\"Yoruba religion\">Yoruba</a> god of smallpox, <a href=\"/wiki/Sopona\" title=\"Sopona\">Sopona</a>, was associated with the color red.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Finsen_and_the_red_light\">Finsen and the red light</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Smallpox_demon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Finsen and the red light\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The red treatment was given scientific authority by Finsen, who claimed that the treatment of smallpox patients with red light reduced the severity of scarring, and later developed rules governing erythrotherapy (Finsen, 1901). It lingered on into the 1930s, although other workers declared it to be useless.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Smallpox_demon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite id=\"Aoki\" class=\"citation book\">Aoki, Naomi (2002).  Manabu Ohishi, eds. <i>\u30d3\u30b8\u30e5\u30a2\u30eb\u30fb\u30ef\u30a4\u30c9\u6c5f\u6238\u6642\u4ee3\u9928</i> <bdi lang=\"ja\">\u30f4\u30a3\u30b8\u30e5\u30a2\u30eb\u3000\u30ef\u30a4\u30c9\u3000\u6c5f\u6238\u6642\u4ee3\u9928</bdi> &#91;<i>Visual Wide Edo Book</i>&#93;. Shogakkan. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-4-09-623021-3\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-4-09-623021-3\">978-4-09-623021-3</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=%E3%83%93%E3%82%B8%E3%83%A5%E3%82%A2%E3%83%AB%E3%83%BB%E3%83%AF%E3%82%A4%E3%83%89%E6%B1%9F%E6%88%B8%E6%99%82%E4%BB%A3%E9%A4%A8+%E3%83%B4%E3%82%A3%E3%82%B8%E3%83%A5%E3%82%A2%E3%83%AB%E3%80%80%E3%83%AF%E3%82%A4%E3%83%89%E3%80%80%E6%B1%9F%E6%88%B8%E6%99%82%E4%BB%A3%E9%A4%A8&amp;rft.pub=Shogakkan&amp;rft.date=2002&amp;rft.isbn=978-4-09-623021-3&amp;rft.aulast=Aoki&amp;rft.aufirst=Naomi&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASmallpox+demon\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span><span class=\"citation-comment\" style=\"display:none; color:#33aa33; margin-left:0.3em\">CS1 maint: Uses editors parameter (<a href=\"/wiki/Category:CS1_maint:_Uses_editors_parameter\" title=\"Category:CS1 maint: Uses editors parameter\">link</a>) </span